our decision. We have never before encountered defiance of a remand order, and we hope never to see it again. Members of the Board must count themselves lucky that [the Petitioner] has not asked us to hold them in contempt. . . . The Board seemed to think that we had issued

an advisory opinion, and that faced with a conflict between our views and those of the Attorney General it should follow the latter. Yet it should not be necessary to remind the Board, all of whose members are lawyers, that the “judicial Power” under Article III of the

Constitution is one to make conclusive decisions, not subject to disapproval or revision by another branch of government. This discussion may be in the weeds for non-lawyers, but let me distill it to its essence: In 1803, Chief Justice John Marshall held in Marbury v. Madison

that actions by the executive branch are subject to review by the judicial branch. Marbury v. Madison is the most important decision in American jurisprudence. In telling the Board of Immigration Appeals to ignore the 7th Circuit’s Order, Barr was ignoring the foundational case

in American jurisprudence. You can understand why Judge Easterbrook was furious with the Board of Immigration Appeals for ignoring the 7th Circuit’s order. For those lawyers in the crowd, the opinion is worth reading through the end. Judge Easterbrook was not amused. Bill Barr

is not above the law, though he is currently acting as though he is. The four Assistant US Attorneys who withdrew from the case (and resigned, in one case), show us the way. Mass resignations are an option if Bill Barr continues to subvert the mission and integrity of the
Department of Justice. It's not an attractive option, but it’s an option. In the meantime, “Plan A” by many is to keep the House, flip the Senate, and defeat Trump.

@realDonaldTrump The gravity of Barr’s intervention in the Roger Stone sentencing warped the fabric of democracy on Wednesday. In an astounding display of hubris, Trump tweeted his “congratulations” to Barr for “taking charge” of the Roger Stone sentencing. (For good measure,

Trump also tweeted that “even Robert Mueller lied to Congress.”) As expected, Republicans excused and rationalized Trump’s use of Barr for political purposes. They cited Trump’s “right to free speech,” concern about “overzealous prosecutions,” and lack of concern “as long as the

judge has the final decision.” Compare Republicans’ “so what” attitude about Trump’s blatant corruption of the Roger Stone sentencing to their reaction when former Attorney General Loretta Lynch visited Bill Clinton for fifteen minutes when Hillary was subject of an FBI

investigation. Despite zero evidence that Lynch and Bill Clinton discussed the investigation of Hillary’s emails, Republicans were outraged. They are nothing if not hypocrites in all they do and say. Calls for Barr’s impeachment began gaining steam on Wednesday as the House

Judiciary Committee demanded that he appear to explain the DOJ’s handling of the Stone sentencing. Barr agreed to appear before the Judiciary Committee in late March. NBC News, “Barr agrees to testify before House Judiciary Committee in March, Nadler says.” Barr’s abandonment

of the rule of law has been lambasted by the press, law school professors, career prosecutors, and ethics advocacy groups. Bill Barr doesn’t care about the criticism. He has endured worse in the service of Trump. Barr is motivated by a twisted religious fanaticism.

In a now-infamous speech at Notre Dame University, Barr said, "The traditional Judeo-Christian moral system [of the United States] was [under attack from] secularists and their allies among progressives who have marshalled all the force of mass communications, popular

culture, the entertainment industry and academia." In other words, the Attorney General views himself as a foot soldier in a holy war. What could go wrong with that? I mean, it’s not like the Founders didn’t bend over backward to insulate the federal government from control by

religious factions. See, e.g., the first words of The First Amendment to the Constitution, (“Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion.”) I am considering starting a “GoFundMe” campaign to buy Bill Barr a copy of the Constitution that includes the Bill

of Rights; he apparently has only the original text without amendments. Barr is particularly dangerous because he holds extreme views about the “unitary executive” theory in which the president is not subject to congressional or judicial oversight. In a little-noticed development

three weeks back, a conservative federal judge rebuked Bill Barr for telling a federal agency it could ignore an order from a federal appeals court. See Jorge Baez-Sanchez v. William Barr, No. 19-1642 (7th Cir. Jan. 23, 2020). In that case, Judge Easterbrook of the 7th Circuit

Court of Appeals was aghast by Bill Barr’s apparent instruction to the Immigration Appeals Board to ignore an order by the 7th Circuit. Barr suggested that the Board could ignore the 7th Circuit’s order because its decision was “incorrect.” Judge Easterbrook had this to say about
